# Persistence Testing Standards

Use these rules for all tests under `tests/Capability/**/Infrastructure/Persistence/**`.

## Core Requirements

- Repository and query-builder tests MUST use real database execution.
- Tests MUST run in the project containerized test environment.
- Tests MUST use fixture generators/builders for setup data whenever possible.
- Tests MUST assert behavior and query outcomes (returned rows/counts/state changes), not call choreography.

## Mocking Policy

- You MUST NOT mock database operation dependencies in persistence tests:
  - `Doctrine\DBAL\Connection`
  - Doctrine query builder classes
  - query-builder factories
  - Doctrine entity managers/registries used for DB operations
- `TenantContextInterface` MAY be mocked only for narrowly scoped SQL-shape tests.
- Default pattern is integration style with `AppTestCase` and `setTenantId()`.

## Tenant Coverage

- Tenant-aware persistence tests MUST include:
  - positive same-tenant assertions
  - negative cross-tenant isolation assertions

## Isolation and Determinism

- Each test MUST own its setup data and avoid reliance on shared mutable state.
- Use unique identifiers/codes/names per test case.
- Avoid assertions that depend on implicit ordering unless order is explicitly set in query logic.

## Preferred Pattern

- Extend `App\Tests\AppTestCase`.
- Resolve repositories/builders from the container where practical.
- Create setup data via `FixtureGenerator`.
- Set tenant via `$this->setTenantId(...)`.
- Verify persisted/retrieved data using real DB-backed execution.
